One of the foundations of PKI infrastructure is Time. The system clock defines whether a certificate is valid or not. Hence in IOS the clock must be made authoritative or trustworthy. Without an authoritative source of time PKI function will not work as expected. PKI certificates will be invalid/expired if there is a time mismatch with PKI server. May expect authentication failure.

The WLC is unable to process incoming traffic and may reboot.
Consistent depletion of buffers will cause drops and delays in passing client and management traffic resulting in AP drops and loss of connection to the WLC.
If buffer breach persists it will lead HA AP SSO failure causing the secondary controller to reload or other unexpected behaviors.
Client devices that do not support Fast Transition on the WLAN will fail to connect.
The client device will not be able to connect to the wireless network. Another connection attempt may also fail depending if the response is the expected value.
This will likely cause a crash on the wireless LAN controller.
It is possible more than one AP is impacted.
The WLC will not be able to use the intended AVC protocol pack and will revert to the original pack. This could cause loss in application visibility and control data.
Clients will not be able to get to RUN state on the anchored WLAN.
The control and data path between anchor and foreign controllers is down like due to network connectivity issue. Clientd that fail to anchor will likely be stuck in DHCP_REQD state.

The message indicates loss of network connectivity between the WLC and the export anchors for the guest LAN mentioned on the message. This would result in clients not getting anchored leaving them in DHCP_REQD state.

If message is seen when APs are registering to the controller this will lead to longer maintenance window or downtime. If this is seen when pre-downloading the code to APs there won't be a downtime but eventually APs won't be able to get upgraded to match code on controller.

WLC unable to create software timer object. Consistent display of these messages is typically associated with timer leak. During the leak clients may fail to associate but once timers are exhausted WLC will likely crash.
WLC stops accepting any new clients associations (or re-associations) due to depletion of timers. Once the timers drop to 0 it will likely experience a crash.
This is an early indicator that the dataplane buffers are getting exhausted.

This message is seen when crashinfo for the DataPlane Core is not available. This could be a silent crash for the given core or simply that another dataplane core than the one listed in the message has crashed.
The wireless LAN controller fails to write on flash.This message  has been seen in conjunction with certification missing on WLC or flash corruption which prevents upgrade or configuration change.

Most often it is part of system initialization which resolves itself as system goes through its initialization. Persistent messages however could indicate problems with the file system with accessing configuration or managing software (upgrade/downgrade) of the system.
